    "code": "J45.901",
    "rawCode": "J45901",
    "shortDesc": "Unspecified asthma with (acute) exacerbation",
    "longDesc": "Unspecified asthma with (acute) exacerbation",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes asthma that has suddenly gotten worse (called an exacerbation or flare-up), but the specific type or underlying cause of the asthma hasn't been clearly identified or documented. During an exacerbation, the airways in the lungs become inflamed and narrowed, making it harder to breathe, causing wheezing, coughing, chest tightness, and shortness of breath that may require urgent medical attention.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonologists, allergists, emergency medicine doctors, and primary care physicians use this code when treating patients with acute asthma attacks. It commonly appears in hospital emergency department visits, urgent care encounters, and hospital admissions, and is frequently seen on EOB statements because asthma exacerbations often require immediate medical intervention and may involve expensive emergency or inpatient care.",
