    "rawCode": "J9600",
    "shortDesc": "Acute respiratory failure, unsp w hypoxia or hypercapnia",
    "longDesc": "Acute respiratory failure, unspecified whether with hypoxia or hypercapnia",
    "plainEnglish": "Acute respiratory failure means your lungs have suddenly stopped working well enough to get oxygen into your blood or remove carbon dioxide from it, and doctors haven't documented whether your oxygen levels are low, your carbon dioxide levels are high, or both. This is a serious emergency where your body isn't getting enough oxygen or is building up too much carbon dioxide, which can happen from infections like pneumonia, severe asthma attacks, heart problems, or injuries to the lungs or chest.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, ICU doctors, pulmonologists, and hospitalists commonly use this code when treating patients in acute respiratory distress requiring immediate intervention like oxygen therapy or mechanical ventilation. It frequently appears on hospital bills and ICU admission records but is less common on routine outpatient EOBs since respiratory failure typically requires hospitalization.",
